\f0\fs26 \cf0 A 
\b protein microarray
\b0  (or 
\b protein chip
\b0 ) is a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High-throughput_screening"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 high-throughput}} method used to track the interactions and activities of proteins, and to determine their function, and determining function on a large scale.
\fs22 \cf2 [1]
\fs26 \cf0  Its main advantage lies in the fact that large numbers of proteins can be tracked in parallel. The chip consists of a support surface such as a glass slide, nitrocellulose membrane, bead, or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microtitre_plate"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 microtitre plate}}, to which an array of capture proteins is bound.
\fs22 \cf2 [2]
\fs26 \cf0  {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probe"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Probe}} molecules, typically labeled with a fluorescent dye, are added to the array. Any reaction between the probe and the immobilised protein emits a fluorescent signal that is read by a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laser_scanning"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 laser scanner}}.
\fs22 \cf2 [3]
\fs26 \cf0  Protein microarrays are rapid, automated, economical, and highly sensitive, consuming small quantities of samples and reagents.
\fs22 \cf2 [4]
\fs26 \cf0  The high-throughput technology behind the protein microarray was relatively easy to develop since it is based on the previously-developed {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA_microarray"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 DNA microarray}} technology.
